Syntax Differences
Opening console in web browser to plug in commands
C-ish language

not necessarily ending with semi colons, but for the most part need to

type/typeof(5.5)
5.5 and 5 are both numbers instead of floats and ints
basic arithmetic works naturally
1+1;
10*2;
including uneven division and modulo
type of (NaN) (not a number)
‘number’
booleans are lower case
true;

equality is === inequality is !==
1 === 1
1 !== ‘1’
1 == ‘1’

“hi” + “mom” + 5 + 6 vs. 5 + 6 + “hi” + “mom”

null == undefined; = true
null === undefined; = false

.charAt(0) (same as indexes)
can also use [3]
“string”.length = 6
“Hello world”.substring(0,5) = “hello”

variables are defined with var someVar = 5;
without the ‘var’ the variable is named globally
variables declared without being assigned are set to undefined
if you want to declare a couple of variables, use a comma separator
var someFourthVar = 2, someFifthVar = 4;
performing math on variables
someVar += 5;
someVar *= 10;
adding or subtracting 1
numVar++ prints value then adds one
++numVar adds one then prints value
adding values to Array
myArray.push(“world”)
Arrays know their length
myArray.length

in javascript, objects and dictionaries are the same thing

because dictionaries are objects, they know their attributes
myObj.favString
